))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    'Every function in JavaScript creates its own scope — a private space for its variables.',
    'A closure happens when an inner function uses a variable from its outer function. The inner function "closes over" that variable.',
    'This is why useState works: the setter function closes over the state value and remembers it between renders.',
    'Event handlers in React are closures — they close over the current state values at the time of creation.',
    'IIFE (Immediately Invoked Function Expression) is a closure pattern used for encapsulation.',
], PURPLE)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'What is a closure? Give a real example.',
    'A closure is when a function retains access to variables from its outer scope even after the outer function has finished executing. '
    'The inner function "closes over" those variables. '
    'A practical example in React: when I write a click handler inside a component, '
    'it is a closure — it has access to the component\'s state and props even though '
    'it runs later when the user clicks. Another example is a counter factory — '
    'a function that returns another function, and the inner function remembers the count variable. '
    'Closures are the reason React hooks like useState and useCallback work the way they do.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    '// Arrow functions',
    'const add = (a, b) => a + b;           // one-liner, auto return',
    'const greet = (name) => {              // multi-line needs explicit return',
    '  const msg = `Hello, ${name}!`;',
    '  return msg;',
    '};',
    '',
    '// Closure — function remembers outer variable',
    'function makeCounter() {',
    '  let count = 0;              // count lives in makeCounter\'s scope',
    '  return function() {         // inner function closes over count',
    '    count++;',
    '    return count;',
    '  };',
    '}',
    'const counter = makeCounter();',
    'console.log(counter());  // 1',
    'console.log(counter());  // 2  (count is remembered!)',
    'console.log(counter());  // 3',
    '',
    '// Closure in React — event handler closes over state',
    "// Every time you write: onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}",
    "// That arrow function is a closure over 'count'",
    '',
    '// Practical closure — debounce function',
    'function debounce(fn, delay) {',
    '  let timer;                         // timer is closed over',
    '  return function(...args) {',
    '    clearTimeout(timer);             // cancel previous call',
    '    timer = setTimeout(() => fn(...args), delay);',
    '  };',
    '}',
    'const search = debounce((query) => fetchResults(query), 300);',
]))
story.append(PageBreak())

# ── TOPIC 4: Async/Await and Promises ─────────────────────────
story.append(topic_header('Topic 4 — Async/Await and Promises', 'How JavaScript handles time-consuming operations', AMBER_LIGHT, AMBER_DARK))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('PLAIN ENGLISH EXPLANATION'))
story.append(body(
    'JavaScript runs one line at a time. But some operations take time — fetching data from an API, '
    'reading a file, waiting for a timer. If JavaScript waited for each one, the page would freeze. '
    'Promises represent a value that will be available in the future — it is either pending, fulfilled, or rejected. '
    'Async/Await is a cleaner way to write code that waits for Promises. '
    'In React, you use async/await every time you call an API inside useEffect.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    'JavaScript is single-threaded — one operation at a time. Async operations are handed off to the browser\'s Web APIs.',
    'A Promise has 3 states: pending (waiting), fulfilled (success with value), rejected (failed with error).',
    '.then() runs when the Promise fulfills. .catch() runs when it rejects. .finally() always runs.',
    'async makes a function always return a Promise. await pauses execution inside that function until the Promise resolves.',
    'Always use try/catch with async/await to handle errors — unhandled rejections can crash your app.',
    'Promise.all() runs multiple async operations in parallel — much faster than sequential awaits.',
], AMBER)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'Explain Promises and async/await. When would you use Promise.all()?',
    'A Promise represents the eventual result of an asynchronous operation — it can be pending, fulfilled, or rejected. '
    'Async/Await is syntactic sugar over Promises that makes async code read like synchronous code. '
    'I prefer async/await over .then() chains because it is easier to read and debug. '
    'I would use Promise.all() when I need to fetch multiple independent pieces of data simultaneously — '
    'for example, fetching a user profile and their order history at the same time. '
    'Promise.all() runs them in parallel and waits for all to complete, '
    'whereas awaiting them sequentially would be much slower. '
    'I always wrap async/await in try/catch for error handling.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    '// Promise — basic usage',
    'const fetchUser = () => {',
    '  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {',
    '    setTimeout(() => {',
    '      resolve({ name: "Vigneswaran", role: "dev" });  // success',
    '      // reject(new Error("Not found"));              // failure',
    '    }, 1000);',
    '  });',
    '};',
    '',
    '// async/await — cleaner syntax',
    'async function loadUserData() {',
    '  try {',
    '    const user = await fetchUser();',
    '    console.log(user.name);  // "Vigneswaran"',
    '  } catch (error) {',
    '    console.error("Failed:", error.message);',
    '  } finally {',
    '    console.log("Done");  // always runs',
    '  }',
    '}',
    '',
    '// Fetch API — how you call real APIs',
    'async function getProducts() {',
    '  try {',
    '    const res = await fetch("https://api.example.com/products");',
    '    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP error: ${res.status}`);',
    '    const data = await res.json();',
    '    return data;',
    '  } catch (err) {',
    '    console.error(err);',
    '    return [];',
    '  }',
    '}',
    '',
    '// Promise.all — parallel fetching (faster)',
    'async function loadDashboard(userId) {',
    '  const [user, orders, notifications] = await Promise.all([',
    '    fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`).then(r => r.json()),',
    '    fetch(`/api/orders/${userId}`).then(r => r.json()),',
    '    fetch(`/api/notifications/${userId}`).then(r => r.json()),',
    '  ]);',
    '  return { user, orders, notifications };',
    '  // All 3 fetch simultaneously — not one after another',
    '}',
]))
story.append(PageBreak())

