# ── TOPIC 5: useState ─────────────────────────────────────────
story.append(topic_header('Topic 5 — useState', 'The hook that makes components interactive', GREEN_LIGHT, TEAL_DARK))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('PLAIN ENGLISH EXPLANATION'))
story.append(body(
    'useState is a React hook that lets a component remember information between renders. '
    'Without useState, every time React re-renders a component, all variables reset to their initial values. '
    'useState stores a value that persists across renders, and when you update it, '
    'React automatically re-renders the component to show the new value. '
    'It is the foundation of all interactivity in React.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    'React stores state outside the component function. Each component instance has its own state slot in React\'s internal storage.',
    'When you call setState, React schedules a re-render. It does NOT update state immediately — state updates are asynchronous.',
    'Never mutate state directly (array.push(), obj.key = value). Always create a new reference. React compares references to detect changes.',
    'Multiple setState calls in one event handler are batched together — React does one re-render, not multiple.',
    'The initial value in useState(initialValue) only runs once on the first render.',
    'For objects and arrays, always spread: setState({ ...prev, key: newValue }) or setState([...prev, newItem]).',
], TEAL_MID)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'Explain useState. Why should you never mutate state directly?',
    'useState is a React hook that declares a state variable that persists between renders. '
    'It returns two things: the current value and a setter function. '
    'When you call the setter, React schedules a re-render with the new value. '
    'You should never mutate state directly — like using push() on a state array — '
    'because React uses reference equality to detect state changes. '
    'If you mutate the same array, the reference does not change, '
    'so React does not know the state changed and does not re-render. '
    'Always create a new array or object: setItems([...items, newItem]). '
    'This is also why the spread operator is used so much in React state management.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    "import { useState } from 'react';",
    '',
    '// Basic counter',
    'function Counter() {',
    '  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);',
    '  return (',
    '    <div>',
    '      <p>Count: {count}</p>',
    '      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>+</button>',
    '      <button onClick={() => setCount(count - 1)}>-</button>',
    '      <button onClick={() => setCount(0)}>Reset</button>',
    '    </div>',
    '  );',
    '}',
    '',
    '// WRONG — mutating state directly (React will not re-render)',
    '// const [items, setItems] = useState(["a", "b"]);',
    '// items.push("c");  // BAD — same reference, React ignores it',
    '',
    '// CORRECT — always create new array/object',
    'function TodoList() {',
    '  const [todos, setTodos] = useState([]);',
    '  const [input, setInput] = useState("");',
    '',
    '  const addTodo = () => {',
    '    setTodos([...todos, { id: Date.now(), text: input, done: false }]);',
    '    setInput("");',
    '  };',
    '',
    '  const toggleTodo = (id) => {',
    '    setTodos(todos.map(t =>',
    '      t.id === id ? { ...t, done: !t.done } : t',
    '    ));',
    '  };',
    '',
    '  return (',
    '    <div>',
    '      <input value={input} onChange={e => setInput(e.target.value)} />',
    '      <button onClick={addTodo}>Add</button>',
    '      {todos.map(t => (',
    '        <div key={t.id} onClick={() => toggleTodo(t.id)}',
    '          style={{ textDecoration: t.done ? "line-through" : "none" }}>',
    '          {t.text}',
    '        </div>',
    '      ))}',
    '    </div>',
    '  );',
    '}',
]))
story.append(PageBreak())

# ── TOPIC 6: useEffect ────────────────────────────────────────
story.append(topic_header('Topic 6 — useEffect', 'Side effects — API calls, subscriptions, DOM updates', BLUE_LIGHT, BLUE_DARK))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('PLAIN ENGLISH EXPLANATION'))
story.append(body(
    'useEffect runs code after React renders the component. '
    'It is used for anything that happens outside React\'s rendering process — '
    'calling an API, setting up an event listener, updating the document title, '
    'starting a timer, or subscribing to a data source. '
    'Without useEffect, you cannot do anything asynchronous in a React component.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    'useEffect runs AFTER the component renders and the DOM is updated — not during rendering.',
    'The dependency array [] controls when it runs: no array = runs after every render. [] = runs once on mount. [value] = runs when value changes.',
    'The cleanup function (return () => {}) runs before the next effect and when the component unmounts. Always cleanup subscriptions and timers.',
    'You cannot make the useEffect callback itself async — create an async function inside it and call it.',
    'useEffect with [] is equivalent to componentDidMount in class components.',
    'Stale closure bug: if you use state inside useEffect but forget to add it to the dependency array, you get old values.',
], BLUE)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'When does useEffect run? Explain the dependency array.',
    'useEffect runs after React finishes rendering and the DOM is updated. '
    'The dependency array controls how often it runs. '
    'With no dependency array, it runs after every single render — rarely what you want. '
    'With an empty array [], it runs only once when the component mounts — '
    'perfect for initial API calls. '
    'With specific values like [userId], it runs whenever userId changes — '
    'perfect for fetching data when a prop changes. '
    'I always include a cleanup function to cancel subscriptions or clear timers '
    'to prevent memory leaks when the component unmounts. '
    'One important note: you cannot make the useEffect callback itself async — '
    'you need to define an async function inside it and call it immediately.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    "import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';",
    '',
    'function UserProfile({ userId }) {',
    '  const [user, setUser]       = useState(null);',
    '  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);',
    '  const [error, setError]     = useState(null);',
    '',
    '  useEffect(() => {',
    '    // Cannot make the callback itself async',
    '    // So define async function inside and call it',
    '    async function fetchUser() {',
    '      try {',
    '        setLoading(true);',
    '        const res  = await fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`);',
    '        if (!res.ok) throw new Error("User not found");',
    '        const data = await res.json();',
    '        setUser(data);',
    '      } catch (err) {',
    '        setError(err.message);',
    '      } finally {',
    '        setLoading(false);',
    '      }',
    '    }',
    '',
    '    fetchUser();',
    '  }, [userId]);  // Re-runs whenever userId changes',
    '',
    '  if (loading) return <p>Loading...</p>;',
    '  if (error)   return <p>Error: {error}</p>;',
    '  if (!user)   return null;',
    '  return <h1>{user.name}</h1>;',
    '}',
    '',
    '// Cleanup example — event listener',
    'function WindowSize() {',
    '  const [width, setWidth] = useState(window.innerWidth);',
    '',
    '  useEffect(() => {',
    '    const handleResize = () => setWidth(window.innerWidth);',
    '    window.addEventListener("resize", handleResize);',
    '',
    '    return () => {',
    '      window.removeEventListener("resize", handleResize);',
    '      // Cleanup runs when component unmounts — prevents memory leak',
    '    };',
    '  }, []);  // Only runs once on mount',
    '',
    '  return <p>Width: {width}px</p>;',
    '}',
]))
story.append(PageBreak())

# ── TOPIC 7: useContext ────────────────────────────────────────
story.append(topic_header('Topic 7 — useContext', 'Share state across components without prop drilling', PURPLE_LIGHT, PURPLE_DARK))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('PLAIN ENGLISH EXPLANATION'))
story.append(body(
    'Imagine you have a user\'s login information at the top of your app. '
    'You need it in the navbar, the sidebar, the dashboard, and the profile page — '
    'all deep inside the component tree. '
    'Without Context, you would pass it as a prop through every component in between — called prop drilling. '
    'useContext lets you create a shared "store" that any component can read directly, '
    'no matter how deeply nested it is.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    'Context has three parts: React.createContext() creates the context. Provider wraps the components that need access. useContext() reads the value.',
    'Any component inside the Provider can access the context value without receiving it as a prop.',
    'When the context value changes, ALL components consuming that context re-render. Use it for truly global state.',
    'Context is not a replacement for all state management. Use it for theme, auth, language. Use Redux for complex shared state.',
    'You can have multiple contexts in one app — one for auth, one for theme, one for cart.',
], PURPLE)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'What is the difference between useContext and Redux? When would you use each?',
    'useContext is React\'s built-in solution for sharing state across components without prop drilling. '
    'It is ideal for simple global values like the current user, theme (dark/light mode), or language preference. '
    'Redux is a more powerful external library suited for complex state — '
    'multiple interacting slices of state, middleware for side effects, '
    'time-travel debugging, and when multiple parts of the app update the same data. '
    'In my HCL projects, I used Redux Toolkit for complex shared state like user session, '
    'permissions, and notification data — because it gave us a clear structure and devtools support. '
    'For simpler things like theme toggling, useContext is cleaner and avoids the Redux boilerplate.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    "import { createContext, useContext, useState } from 'react';",
    '',
    '// Step 1: Create the context',
    'const ThemeContext = createContext("light");',
    '',
    '// Step 2: Provider — wrap the app (or part of it)',
    'function App() {',
    '  const [theme, setTheme] = useState("light");',
    '',
    '  return (',
    '    <ThemeContext.Provider value={{ theme, setTheme }}>',
    '      <Navbar />',
    '      <Dashboard />',
    '    </ThemeContext.Provider>',
    '  );',
    '}',
    '',
    '// Step 3: Consumer — any nested component reads context directly',
    'function Navbar() {',
    '  const { theme, setTheme } = useContext(ThemeContext);',
    '  return (',
    '    <nav style={{ background: theme === "dark" ? "#333" : "#fff" }}>',
    '      <button onClick={() => setTheme(theme === "dark" ? "light" : "dark")}>',
    '        Toggle theme',
    '      </button>',
    '    </nav>',
    '  );',
    '}',
    '',
    '// Dashboard does not need to know about theme at all',
    'function Dashboard() {',
    '  return <div><UserCard /></div>;',
    '}',
    '',
    '// UserCard can still access theme directly — no prop drilling',
    'function UserCard() {',
    '  const { theme } = useContext(ThemeContext);',
    '  return <div className={`card card--${theme}`}>User Info</div>;',
    '}',
]))
story.append(PageBreak())

# ── TOPIC 8: Custom Hooks ─────────────────────────────────────
story.append(topic_header('Topic 8 — Custom Hooks', 'Reusable logic extracted from components', GREEN_LIGHT, TEAL_DARK))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('PLAIN ENGLISH EXPLANATION'))
story.append(body(
    'A custom hook is a JavaScript function that starts with "use" and contains React hooks inside it. '
    'It lets you extract repeated logic from components and reuse it. '
    'For example, if multiple components fetch data from an API in the same way, '
    'you can extract that logic into a useFetch hook and use it in all of them. '
    'Custom hooks are how senior developers write clean, DRY React code.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    'Custom hooks are just functions — they are not a special React API. The "use" prefix tells React (and linters) to apply hook rules.',
    'They can call any built-in hooks: useState, useEffect, useContext, etc.',
    'They encapsulate stateful logic — not JSX. They return values/functions, not components.',
    'Each component using a custom hook gets its own isolated state — hooks are not shared between components.',
    'Custom hooks are the correct way to share stateful logic. Context shares state values. Hooks share logic.',
], TEAL_MID)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'What are custom hooks? When and why would you create one?',
    'Custom hooks are functions that start with "use" and encapsulate reusable stateful logic. '
    'I create a custom hook when I find myself writing the same useState and useEffect pattern '
    'in multiple components. For example, in my HCL project I had multiple components '
    'that all needed to fetch data, handle loading states, and handle errors. '
    'I extracted that into a useFetch hook — it accepts a URL and returns data, loading, and error. '
    'Every component that needed API data just called useFetch with a URL. '
    'This removed 20+ lines of duplicate code from each component. '
    'The key point is: custom hooks share logic, not state. '
    'Each component using useFetch gets its own independent state.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    "import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';",
    '',
    '// Custom hook — useFetch',
    '// Reusable data fetching with loading + error handling',
    'function useFetch(url) {',
    '  const [data, setData]       = useState(null);',
    '  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);',
    '  const [error, setError]     = useState(null);',
    '',
    '  useEffect(() => {',
    '    async function fetchData() {',
    '      try {',
    '        setLoading(true);',
    '        const res  = await fetch(url);',
    '        if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`Error: ${res.status}`);',
    '        const json = await res.json();',
    '        setData(json);',
    '      } catch (err) {',
    '        setError(err.message);',
    '      } finally {',
    '        setLoading(false);',
    '      }',
    '    }',
    '    fetchData();',
    '  }, [url]);',
    '',
    '  return { data, loading, error };',
    '}',
    '',
    '// Usage — any component can use this',
    'function ProductList() {',
    '  const { data: products, loading, error } = useFetch("/api/products");',
    '',
    '  if (loading) return <p>Loading...</p>;',
    '  if (error)   return <p>Error: {error}</p>;',
    '  return <ul>{products.map(p => <li key={p.id}>{p.name}</li>)}</ul>;',
    '}',
    '',
    'function UserList() {',
    '  const { data: users, loading } = useFetch("/api/users");',
    '  if (loading) return <p>Loading users...</p>;',
    '  return <ul>{users.map(u => <li key={u.id}>{u.name}</li>)}</ul>;',
    '}',
    '// Both components share the LOGIC of useFetch',
    '// but each has their own independent state',
]))
story.append(PageBreak())

# ── TOPIC 9: useCallback and useMemo ─────────────────────────
story.append(topic_header('Topic 9 — useCallback and useMemo', 'Performance optimisation hooks', AMBER_LIGHT, AMBER_DARK))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('PLAIN ENGLISH EXPLANATION'))
story.append(body(
    'Every time a component re-renders, all the functions and computed values inside it are recreated. '
    'Usually this is fine. But if a function is passed as a prop to a child component, '
    'or if a computation is very expensive, recreating it every render wastes performance. '
    'useCallback remembers a function between renders so it is only recreated when its dependencies change. '
    'useMemo remembers a computed value between renders for the same reason.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    'useCallback(fn, deps) — returns the same function reference as long as deps have not changed.',
    'useMemo(fn, deps) — returns the same computed value as long as deps have not changed.',
    'Without useCallback, passing a function as a prop creates a new reference every render, causing child re-renders even when data has not changed.',
    'useCallback is most useful with React.memo() — a child wrapped in React.memo only re-renders if its props change. But if the function prop is always new, it re-renders anyway.',
    'Do NOT add useCallback/useMemo everywhere. Premature optimisation adds complexity. Only use them when you measure a real performance problem.',
], AMBER)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'Explain useCallback and useMemo. When should you actually use them?',
    'useCallback memoizes a function so it keeps the same reference between renders unless its dependencies change. '
    'useMemo memoizes a computed value for the same reason. '
    'I use useCallback when passing a function as a prop to a child component wrapped in React.memo — '
    'this prevents unnecessary child re-renders. '
    'I use useMemo when a computation is expensive — like filtering or sorting a large array — '
    'so it does not recalculate on every render when unrelated state changes. '
    'However, I do not add these hooks everywhere. '
    'React is already fast. Adding useCallback and useMemo prematurely '
    'actually makes code harder to read without real performance benefit. '
    'I only add them when I have identified an actual performance problem using React DevTools Profiler.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    "import { useState, useCallback, useMemo, memo } from 'react';",
    '',
    '// Child component wrapped in memo',
    '// Only re-renders if its props actually change',
    'const SearchButton = memo(function SearchButton({ onClick }) {',
    '  console.log("SearchButton rendered");',
    '  return <button onClick={onClick}>Search</button>;',
    '});',
    '',
    'function SearchPage() {',
    '  const [query, setQuery] = useState("");',
    '  const [results, setResults] = useState([]);',
    '',
    '  // Without useCallback: new function reference every render',
    '  // SearchButton would re-render on every keystroke',
    '  const handleSearch = useCallback(() => {',
    '    fetch(`/api/search?q=${query}`)                ',
    '      .then(r => r.json())',
    '      .then(setResults);',
    '  }, [query]);  // Only new function when query changes',
    '',
    '  // useMemo — expensive calculation only re-runs when results change',
    '  const sortedResults = useMemo(() => {',
    '    console.log("Sorting...");',
    '    return [...results].sort((a, b) => a.title.localeCompare(b.title));',
    '  }, [results]);',
    '',
    '  return (',
    '    <div>',
    '      <input value={query} onChange={e => setQuery(e.target.value)} />',
    '      <SearchButton onClick={handleSearch} />',
    '      {sortedResults.map(r => <div key={r.id}>{r.title}</div>)}',
    '    </div>',
    '  );',
    '}',
]))
story.append(PageBreak())

# ── TOPIC 10: Virtual DOM ─────────────────────────────────────
story.append(topic_header('Topic 10 — Virtual DOM and Reconciliation', 'How React updates the UI efficiently', BLUE_LIGHT, BLUE_DARK))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('PLAIN ENGLISH EXPLANATION'))
story.append(body(
    'Directly manipulating the real browser DOM is slow. '
    'Every time you change the DOM, the browser has to recalculate layouts and repaint pixels. '
    'React solves this with the Virtual DOM — a lightweight JavaScript copy of the real DOM. '
    'When state changes, React updates the Virtual DOM first, compares it to the previous version '
    '(this comparison is called "diffing" or "reconciliation"), '
    'and then makes only the minimum necessary changes to the real DOM.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    'Virtual DOM is a plain JavaScript object tree that mirrors the real DOM structure.',
    'When state or props change, React creates a NEW Virtual DOM tree.',
    'React\'s diffing algorithm (reconciliation) compares old and new Virtual DOM trees to find what changed.',
    'React updates ONLY the changed parts in the real DOM — called a "patch" or "commit".',
    'The key prop on list items helps React identify which items changed, were added, or removed during diffing.',
    'React 18 introduced concurrent rendering — React can pause, interrupt, and resume rendering work based on priority.',
], BLUE)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'How does the Virtual DOM work? Why is it important?',
    'The Virtual DOM is a lightweight JavaScript representation of the real DOM. '
    'When state or props change in React, React first updates a new Virtual DOM tree. '
    'Then it runs a diffing algorithm called reconciliation — '
    'comparing the new Virtual DOM with the previous snapshot to find exactly what changed. '
    'Finally, React batches all the identified changes and applies only those specific updates '
    'to the real browser DOM in one operation. '
    'This is important because direct DOM manipulation is expensive — '
    'every change triggers browser recalculation of layouts and repaints. '
    'By batching minimal changes, React makes updates much more efficient. '
    'This is also why we need the key prop on list items — '
    'it gives React a stable identity for each item during reconciliation, '
    'so it knows which items are the same, which are new, and which were removed.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    '// Key prop — tells React how to identify each list item',
    '// WITHOUT key — React cannot efficiently diff the list',
    'const bad = items.map(item => <div>{item.name}</div>);',
    '',
    '// WITH key — React tracks each item by its unique id',
    'const good = items.map(item => <div key={item.id}>{item.name}</div>);',
    '',
    '// Never use array index as key when list can reorder/add/remove',
    '// Index as key causes bugs when items are reordered',
    'const buggy = items.map((item, i) => <div key={i}>{item.name}</div>);',
    '',
    '// React.memo — prevents re-render if props have not changed',
    "import { memo } from 'react';",
    '',
    'const ProductCard = memo(function ProductCard({ product }) {',
    '  return (',
    '    <div className="card">',
