# ── TOPIC 12: Server vs Client Components ────────────────────
story.append(topic_header('Topic 12 — Server vs Client Components', 'The most important Next.js concept', RED_LIGHT, RED_DARK))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('PLAIN ENGLISH EXPLANATION'))
story.append(body(
    'In plain React, everything runs in the browser. '
    'In Next.js App Router, components run on the server by default. '
    'A Server Component runs on the server, fetches data, and sends finished HTML to the browser — '
    'no JavaScript bundle sent to the client. '
    'A Client Component runs in the browser and can use React hooks, handle events, and be interactive. '
    'You make a component a Client Component by adding "use client" at the top of the file.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    'Server Components are the default. They run only on the server. They cannot use useState, useEffect, or any browser APIs.',
    '"use client" at the top of a file marks it as a Client Component — it runs in the browser like regular React.',
    'Server Components can import Client Components. But Client Components CANNOT import Server Components.',
    'Server Components reduce JavaScript bundle size — their code never goes to the browser.',
    'Server Components can directly await database queries or API calls — no useEffect needed.',
    'The boundary between server and client is explicit — this is one of the most common interview topics in Next.js.',
], RED_DARK)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'What is the difference between Server Components and Client Components in Next.js?',
    'In Next.js App Router, all components are Server Components by default. '
    'Server Components run exclusively on the server — they can fetch data directly with async/await, '
    'access databases, and they never send their component code to the browser, '
    'reducing the JavaScript bundle size. '
    'Client Components are marked with "use client" at the top of the file. '
    'They run in the browser and can use React hooks like useState and useEffect, '
    'handle user events, and access browser APIs. '
    'My rule of thumb is: if the component needs interactivity — onClick, form inputs, useState — '
    'it needs "use client". Everything else can be a Server Component. '
    'Server Components can import and render Client Components, but not vice versa. '
    'This distinction is important because it helps keep the client-side bundle small and pages fast.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    '// Server Component (default) — runs on server only',
    '// Can use async/await directly, no useEffect needed',
    'export default async function ProductsPage() {',
    '  // This fetch runs on the server — not in the browser',
    '  const products = await fetch("https://api.example.com/products")',
    '    .then(r => r.json());',
    '',
    '  return (',
    '    <div>',
    '      <h1>Products</h1>',
    '      {products.map(p => (',
    '        <ProductCard key={p.id} product={p} />',
    '        // ProductCard can be a Client Component with onClick etc.',
    '      ))}',
    '    </div>',
    '  );',
    '}',
    '',
    '// Client Component — runs in browser',
    '"use client";',
    "import { useState } from 'react';",
    '',
    'export default function ProductCard({ product }) {',
    '  const [added, setAdded] = useState(false);',
    '',
    '  return (',
    '    <div>',
    '      <h2>{product.name}</h2>',
    '      <button onClick={() => setAdded(true)}>',
    '        {added ? "Added!" : "Add to cart"}',
    '      </button>',
    '    </div>',
    '  );',
    '}',
    '',
    '// Rule: Server Component can use Client Component',
    '// Client Component CANNOT use Server Component',
]))
story.append(PageBreak())

# ── TOPIC 13: SSR / SSG / ISR / CSR ──────────────────────────
story.append(topic_header('Topic 13 — SSR, SSG, ISR, CSR', 'Four rendering strategies — know when to use each', PURPLE_LIGHT, PURPLE_DARK))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('PLAIN ENGLISH EXPLANATION'))
story.append(body(
    'These four strategies control when and where your page\'s HTML is generated. '
    'SSG (Static Site Generation) builds the page once at deploy time — fastest, best for content that does not change often. '
    'SSR (Server Side Rendering) builds the page fresh for every request — always up to date, slower. '
    'ISR (Incremental Static Regeneration) is the best of both — static but refreshes in the background every X seconds. '
    'CSR (Client Side Rendering) is what plain React does — browser downloads JS and renders the page.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    'SSG: page built at build time. Fast CDN delivery. Use for: blog posts, docs, marketing pages.',
    'SSR: page built on every request. Always fresh. Use for: dashboards, user-specific pages, live prices.',
    'ISR: page built at build time + refreshes every N seconds. Use for: product listings, news, e-commerce.',
    'CSR: page skeleton delivered, content loads in browser via JS. Use for: private user data, highly interactive apps.',
    'In Next.js App Router: fetch() with no options = SSG. cache: "no-store" = SSR. next: { revalidate: N } = ISR.',
    '"force-dynamic" export = SSR. Default Server Component with fetch = SSG.',
], PURPLE)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'Explain SSR vs SSG vs ISR. When would you choose each?',
    'SSG — Static Site Generation — builds the page once at deploy time. '
    'The HTML is pre-built and served instantly from a CDN. '
    'I use SSG for content that does not change often: blog posts, documentation, landing pages. '
    'SSR — Server Side Rendering — generates fresh HTML on every request. '
    'I use SSR for dashboards, user profile pages, and pages with real-time data like live prices. '
    'ISR — Incremental Static Regeneration — is Next.js\'s most powerful option. '
    'It starts as a static page but automatically regenerates in the background every N seconds. '
    'This gives you CDN-level speed with near-real-time data freshness. '
    'I use ISR for product catalogues and news feeds where data changes every few minutes. '
    'For my portfolio project, I used SSG for all pages since the content does not change, '
    'which gives the best performance score.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    '// SSG — static at build time (default for Server Components)',
    'export default async function BlogPage() {',
    '  const posts = await fetch("https://api.example.com/posts")',
    '    .then(r => r.json());',
    '    // No cache option = SSG by default',
    '  return <PostList posts={posts} />;',
    '}',
    '',
    '// SSR — fresh on every request',
    'export const dynamic = "force-dynamic"; // OR use cache: "no-store"',
    'export default async function DashboardPage() {',
    '  const data = await fetch("https://api.example.com/live", {',
    '    cache: "no-store"  // never cache, always fresh',
    '  }).then(r => r.json());',
    '  return <Dashboard data={data} />;',
    '}',
    '',
    '// ISR — static but refreshes every 60 seconds',
    'export const revalidate = 60;',
    'export default async function ProductsPage() {',
    '  const products = await fetch("https://api.example.com/products", {',
    '    next: { revalidate: 60 }  // regenerate every 60s',
    '  }).then(r => r.json());',
    '  return <ProductGrid products={products} />;',
    '}',
]))
story.append(PageBreak())

# ── TOPIC 14: Server Actions ──────────────────────────────────
story.append(topic_header('Topic 14 — Server Actions', 'Run server code directly from components', AMBER_LIGHT, AMBER_DARK))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('PLAIN ENGLISH EXPLANATION'))
story.append(body(
    'Traditionally, if you wanted to submit a form and save data, '
    'you needed a separate API endpoint — create a route handler, fetch it from the client, handle the response. '
    'Server Actions eliminate this. You write a function with "use server" at the top, '
    'and React/Next.js automatically makes it run on the server when called from the browser. '
    'You can pass this function directly as a form\'s action attribute.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('LOGICAL UNDERSTANDING'))
story += bullet_row([
    '"use server" directive marks a function (or entire file) to run on the server.',
    'Server Actions can be passed directly as action={} on HTML form elements.',
    'After a Server Action mutates data, call revalidatePath() to refresh the cached page data.',
    'Server Actions replace many use cases for API route handlers — but API routes are still better for webhooks, third-party integrations, and custom headers.',
    'Server Actions can be called from Client Components too — useful for button clicks that save data.',
], AMBER)
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('HOW TO SAY IT IN AN INTERVIEW'))
story.append(interview_box(
    'What are Server Actions in Next.js? How are they different from API routes?',
    'Server Actions are async functions marked with "use server" that always run on the server, '
    'even when called from client-side components. '
    'They are typically used for form submissions and data mutations — '
    'creating, updating, or deleting data. '
    'The key benefit is that they eliminate the need to write a separate API route handler '
    'for simple data mutations. I can write the server logic in the same file and pass it '
    'directly as the form\'s action. '
    'After mutating data, I call revalidatePath() to tell Next.js to refresh the cached version of that page. '
    'API routes are still better when I need custom response headers, webhooks, '
    'or integrations with third-party services that need a public URL endpoint.'
))
story.append(sp(6))

story.append(label('CODE EXAMPLE'))
story.append(code_block([
    '// app/actions.ts',
    '"use server";',
    "import { revalidatePath } from 'next/cache';",
    '',
    'export async function createPost(formData: FormData) {',
    '  const title   = formData.get("title") as string;',
    '  const content = formData.get("content") as string;',
    '',
    '  // Save to database (this runs on the server)',
    '  await db.posts.create({ title, content });',
    '',
    '  // Refresh the cached /blog page so new post appears',
    '  revalidatePath("/blog");',
    '}',
    '',
    '// app/blog/new/page.tsx',
    "import { createPost } from '@/app/actions';",
    '',
    'export default function NewPostPage() {',
    '  return (',
    '    // Pass Server Action directly as form action',
    '    <form action={createPost}>',
    '      <input  name="title"   placeholder="Post title" />',
    '      <textarea name="content" placeholder="Content" />',
    '      <button type="submit">Publish</button>',
    '    </form>',
    '    // When submitted, createPost runs on server',
    '    // No fetch call needed, no API route needed',
    '  );',
    '}',
]))
story.append(PageBreak())

